  "prompt": "What does library science do?",
  "response": "Library science is a field of study that focuses on the collection, organization, preservation, and dissemination of information. Here are some key aspects of library science:\n\n1. Information Management\n- Organizing and cataloging books, documents, and digital resources\n- Developing classification systems\n- Creating metadata and search strategies\n\n2. Technology Integration\n- Managing digital libraries and databases\n- Implementing information technology systems\n- Developing digital archiving techniques\n\n3. Research Support\n- Helping researchers find and access information\n- Creating research guides and resources\n- Assisting with information literacy\n\n4. Collection Development\n- Selecting and acquiring new materials\n- Evaluating and maintaining library collections\n- Ensuring diverse and relevant resources\n\n5. User Services\n- Providing reference services\n- Helping patrons locate and use information\n- Designing user-friendly library spaces\n\n6. Preservation\n- Conserving historical documents and materials\n- Digitizing rare or fragile resources\n- Maintaining archives and special collections\n\n7. Information Access\n- Promoting open access to information\n- Supporting intellectual freedom\n- Ensuring equitable access to resources\n\nLibrary science professionals work in various settings like public libraries, academic institutions, museums, archives, government agencies, and digital information centers.",
